 John Schulz explains how planters’ demands for easy credit after abolition were met with shortsighted economic policies. The failure of the expansionary monetary policy of the 1890s not only illuminates Brazil’s history, it also suggests lessons relevant to financial and political decisions being made today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipationxEconomic aspectszBrazil. 0aFinancezBrazilxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxEmancipationxEconomic aspectszBrazil. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030013419340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015049040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300150490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300150490/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY